text: Ok just a few things  Pros: - I actually really like the animation as a whole, it feels faithful to the original books with the characters and the setting itself, if I saw this as I kid back when I was really into captain underpants, it would've blown my mind  -It seems like the film is going to adapt 2 of the books at the same time, which makes sense since they are short and need to pad out some time for more content which is fine by me (Please adapt Flip-o Rama!)  Cons -I will say it now, I don't like Kevin Hart and Thomas Middleditch as George and Harold, I have nothing against these guys, but they just make them sound like adults when I hear George talking all i hear is Kevin hart. I don't understand why they couldn't just get or teen voice actor to perform them instead of just having celebrity voice actors just for the sake of having them if they really wanted celebrities couldn't they go with kids or teens? which goes into my next problem...  -The film unfortunately seems like it's going to suffer from a lot of common modern book/tv series movie adaptations, trying to modernize it with pop music and celebrity voice actors, we only saw a little bit here but I hope that it really doesn't turn out that way and the movie does have funny and awesome moments like the original source material has without relying to much on modernizing it.  That being said I am being cautiously optimistic. How it turns out well.  *Update June 2 2017* I just went to see the film and it was Fantastic!

text: WHOA WHOA WAIT A MINUTE!  Okay, let's see how many references this trailer had to the books. -the prank compilation featured the "krupcakes" prank -the mecha-toilets are here -Dr. Pippi P. Poopy-Pants is here  But the main thing of concern is, are all of these arcs going to be combined into one? Because these were all supposed to be separate titles yet judging from this trailer, Dr. Pippi-Pee is going to concoct the super juice (and the aliens from the source amterial who made it will likely be retconned out of the story), which will end up being dumped down a toilet (ironically true to the source material), except in this instance, Dr. Pippi-Pee won't be using his size-conversion shenanigans, but will either control the mecha-toilet or ally with it (hope it's the latter since the toilet was a hilarious character that doesn't deserve to become some mindless robot).

text: THIS TRAILER GOT ME TRA LA LAAAAAUGHING OUT LOUD!üòÇüòÇüòÇ! I love Shrek, Kungfu Panda, and Madagascar! Seeing that the same people who worked on those films worked on this one, got me very hyped! I see that this is made by DreamWorks Animation, but you know that Fox gotta' get the money from the book based movie to work on their 6th Ice Age film. Need proof? The Diary of a Wimpy Kid Movie came out in 2007, ice age. 2008: Wimpy Kid 2, Ice Age 2. 2009: Took a break. 2010: Ice Age 3. 2011: Wimpy Kid 3. 2012: Ice Age 4. 2013-14: Break 2015: Charlie Brown 2016: Ice Age 5 2017: Captain Underpants 2018?: Ice Age 6 I think that Fox is trying to find a studio that can work on their book movies while Blue Sky works on Ice Age 6. Now I also think that due to the nostalgia and the over abundance of books that Captain Underpants has will be good for them to work on! Or they might do something else because it's looking like their combining all the first 3 books in to one film! And there's also some spin-off books like both of the Super Diper Baby books, Ook and Guk, and   Dogman! But if they get tired of this and work on some other projects as well! This is great and all, but you know what book I want to see get made into the movie? Junie. B . Jones. Why? SHE WAS SO FUNNY WHEN I WAS IN THE FIRST GRADE! This trailer looks so beautiful and follows the books so well, that it's like what was going on in my head when I was reading the books! A movie! This trailer is MILES better than the emoji movie's and boy does it show! There's no pop culture or social media trends that are in this film that'll make it be outdated in anyway, shape, or form! This trailer gets a 10/10 would watch again!

text: ... this is perfect.  The animation is energetic and fluid, which perfectly fits the world its set in. The characters are designed loyally and the voices work very well, especially Mr. Krupp's. Seriously, whoever's voicing him needs a raise. The same goes to Professor Poopypants's VA  The aesthetic is also fitting of the world, and the silliness that's shown here feels like it's absolutely plausible as scenarios in the books. Seriously, which one of us would put it past Mr. Krupp to have that kind of ludicrous security system in his office to keep George and Harold in detention? I think nobody is the answer.  Overall, this is looking like a magnificent recreation of my childhood.

The characters are designed loyally and the voices work very well, especially Mr. Krupp's I've always imagined him with that kind of voice..I mean not the Tra la laaaaa! but hey it works!  The aesthetic is also fitting of the world,  the silliness that's in it feels like its plausible scenarios in the books, oh please be a good movie please! I'd love it so much! "Captain Underpants and the Wrath of the Wicked Wedgie Woman" was my most read book but I see that they're taking from "Attack of the talking toilets" or "Perilous Plot of Professor Poopypants" but it seems to be both...or maybe all of them!? I still love Dav Pilkey and some of the books in a way, but you have to really have a good long think about why this franchise hasn't died yet. Now when this movie was announced I thought it was gonna SUCK. But looking at this trailer now, it actually looks like it will be an ok movie. They seem to have cut down the toilet humour a bit and added in things that are actually funny, the animation looks really freaking great, and Kevin Hart??? Get OUT of here! text: People keep asking why are there adults playing little kids or youth well I'm no expert but for the sake of giving the movie great actors behind it and credibility, also I cannot stress this enough not all kids are great at doing the voice acting and I think personally I'd rather here a person example: like zac effron from the lorax rather than a little kid with his nuts in his throat say you are now captain underpants in a voice of a squirrel nothing wrong with that but doing something like that doesn't always work and isn't very appealing yes I know the actors for the kids may be too old to play the role but they are best suited and give the movie credibility and a familiar voice to many. Sorry if I ranted on about the same points but answer me this have you ever seen a great movie with I kid actor as the protagonist or secondary protagonist as a kid maybe there are a few like zathura but there are many terrible here's one: Fred the movie. It may not be animated but it still is a point, another point is that if all the kids were kids then wouldn't they sound similar and sometimes hard to distinguish in arguments and conversations which are parts of movies and may cause people's ears to bleed if they here 2 or more 10 year olds screaming or yelling at each other and that's my argument.

text: Okay, let me see how I can review this...  Voices: 9.5/10 Every voice, besides Harold, is exactly how I imagined it, but Harold's voice is still so good, it could only be better if the scientists voice was a little different. Animation: 9/10 OR 10/10 The thing with this is that in one scene where the principal says "You've been responsible for one prank after another", the audio was off-sync AND I'm not sure that's what it was attempting to say. I think this is just because it is a trailer, though, so I'll give it's official rating as a 10/10. Overall Plot: 9/10 Pretty much the same as the book, BUT, it's more detailed and such, since the original is a comic book, so yeah. Final Comment: If there is a Flip-O-Rama reference, I will explode with happiness. Overall Rating: 9.75 Notice: This review may be biased due to the fact that I loved Captain Underpants for my entire childhood.

text: My childhood! I swear to GOD if this movie fucking sucks I will be very disappointed. I've read the whole series and I expect it to be very relevant to the story line of the original book(s).  So far the voice actors sound exactly how I expected the characters would've sounded like, so a one up on that! And it stuck with the style which I am very proud of. And the comedy in the trailer seems to fit really well.  The trailer looks really good so far, so I have some pretty decent expectations for when the movie comes out. Well, I guess I should re-read the books before the movie releases. So I can compare and see what they added and took out and what details they missed or got. That'll be enjoyable to take a lane back to Childhood Blvd.

text: The hype is real, but I'm so afraid to get excited. Movies have disappointed me so much in the past. *Especially* movies made for kids and *especially* movies made from books. And don't forget, a lot of the books' humor is from breaking the fourth wall, like when they say something along the lines of, "didn't we do this 9 chapters ago?" which doesn't work the same way in movies. Another big thing the books had but the movie can't possibly have is Flip-O-Rama. You can't flip the pages back and forth if there are no pages, and you can't say "this is the really short chapter that's two words long" if there's no chapters.

Some of the voice acting feels too mature for kids and none of the jokes made me laugh, feeling unfamiliar to the book. I will probably go see it, but I don't have high hopes.

text: Like, even BEYOND the sheer nostalgia factor of this movie? I genuinely think its gonna be a decent movie fore reeling in kids who are unfamiliar with the books: a movie that'll actually be able to capture two audiences. And, much like the ASOUE series on Netflix did, also bring in people interested in the books.  I like the art a lot. This style of art is... kind of a hit and miss. So many venture into the uncanny valley: look at the Smurfs movies. This has a really good and simple cartoonish art style to it: one not only true to the source material, but also appealing to look at. People who watch these movies don't really want to see hyper-realistic eyes and see every pore in a character's face.  Even if I hadn't grown up with these books, I'd be minorly curious to watch it because it looks genuinely light-hearted, fun, and pleasant to look at. I'm looking forward to this.
